Eighteen more merchant-vessels were lying wind-bound in a harbour eight miles further up the coast The cavalry were ordered to embarlr on these. Meanwhile Caesar and the legions set sail at midnight with a fair wind About nine or ten 0’clock next morning he was lying under the beetling cliffs of Britain, which were lined with the armed forces of the enemy. Caesar and his officers had come in the ships of war. While the beavier transport vessels were assembling, Caesar employed the time in laying before his officere his proposed plau of operations, and exhorting them to promptitude in the execution. To attempt a landing where they had arrived was hopeless. But aided both by wind and tide they went on seven miles and, in spite of the opposition of the natives, ellected their landing on an open and flat shore. No sooner were they landed than they dispersed the enemy, bnt

they were not able to follow up their victory for want of the cavalry, who had not arrived.

After the battle the enemy made overtures to Caesar and restored to him his emissary Commius, whom they had thrown into chains on his first landing. Caesar complained of the unpro- voked attach they had made upon him aller having gone out-of their way to send ambassadors to hicnon the Continent. Never- theless he was willing to conclude peace, if they gave him hostages for their good behaviour.

There was some delay about the embarkation of the cavalry, so that Caesar had already been three days in Britain More the eighteen vessels which bore them made their appearance. Just as they came in sight of his campa storm arose which compelled theman, sooner or later, to put back to the Continent.

But the misfortunes of the Romans did not end here. That night the moon was at the full and the tide filled the ships of war which were hauled upon the bsach aad battered the merchant· vessels which lay at anchor, so as to wreclc some and render others unseaworthy. To add to their difficulties they had no supplies, since there had been no idea of wintering in Britain.
